Titanium dioxide ($TiO_2$) functions as a powerful purifier primarily through photocatalysis, a process where light energy triggers a chemical reaction to decompose pollutants. When $TiO_2$ is exposed to ultraviolet (UV) light—and in some cases visible light—it creates reactive species that break down organic compounds, bacteria, and viruses into harmless substances like water and carbon dioxide. [1, 2, 3, 4] 
## Key Purification Mechanisms

* Photocatalytic Oxidation (PCO): Light strikes the $TiO_2$ surface, exciting electrons and creating "holes." These holes react with moisture in the air to form hydroxyl radicals ($\cdot OH$) and superoxide anions ($O_2\cdot^-$), which act as strong oxidizing agents to destroy pollutants.
* Decomposition of Contaminants: It breaks the chemical bonds of volatile organic compounds (VOCs), nitrogen oxides ($NO_x$), and sulfur oxides ($SO_x$), effectively removing smog and offensive odors.
* Antimicrobial Action: The reactive oxygen species (ROS) produced can rupture the cell membranes of bacteria (like E. coli) and fragment the RNA/DNA of viruses (including Coronaviruses), leading to their inactivation.
* Self-Cleaning: On surfaces like building facades or glass, $TiO_2$ makes the surface hydrophilic (water-attracting). Rainwater then spreads out evenly and washes away loosened dirt and organic residue. [1, 2, 3, 5, 6, 7] 

## Practical Applications
$TiO_2$ is integrated into various systems and products for environmental remediation: [3, 8, 9] 

* Air Purifiers: Used in devices like the [Airpura TitanClean](https://www.airpura.com/blogs/air-quality-news/the-definitive-guide-to-photocatalytic-oxidization-in-air-purification) and [SEFU Photocatalyst Filters](https://www.sefunm.com/purification-filter/titanium-dioxide-photocatalyst-filter.html), where $TiO_2$-coated honeycombs or meshes are irradiated by UV lamps to scrub the air of gases and microbes.
* Building Materials: Enhanced paints, tiles, and cement are used on exterior walls to actively reduce local air pollution levels.
* Water Treatment: Used in experimental filters to neutralize chemicals, parasites, and pathogens in pools or wastewater.
* Protective Coatings: Applied to high-touch surfaces in hospitals or public spaces for continuous sterilization. [3, 4, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14] 

## Considerations and Safety
While effective, there are some limitations and safety concerns:

* Light Requirement: Pure $TiO_2$ typically requires UV light; however, doping it with elements like nitrogen or copper can allow it to work under visible light.
* By-products: If the reaction is incomplete, it may release toxic intermediates like formaldehyde or ketones.
* Health Risks: Some agencies like the [International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC)](https://www.teqoya.com/en/photocatalysis-air-purifier/) classify $TiO_2$ as a possible carcinogen if inhaled in large quantities as fine dust. [6, 15, 16, 17] 

